Section 1.2: AddressSpaces

What is an AddressSpace?

```c
// include/exec/memory.h

struct AddressSpace {
    char *name;                    // "system_memory", "system_io"
    MemoryRegion *root;            // Root of the MemoryRegion tree
    struct AddressSpaceDispatch *dispatch;  // FlatView cache
    struct MemoryRegion *current_map;       // Cached region
    struct listener {
        MemoryListener listener;   // For KVM, TCG, VFIO
    } as_listener;
    QTAILQ_ENTRY(AddressSpace) as_link;
};

// Key AddressSpaces in QEMU
extern AddressSpace address_space_memory;  // Guest physical memory
extern AddressSpace address_space_io;      // I/O ports (x86)
```

Why multiple AddressSpaces?

· system_memory: Guest RAM, MMIO, ROM (main)
· system_io: x86 I/O ports (inb/outb)
· cpu-memory-0: Per-CPU memory views (for ARM's TrustZone)

Creating an AddressSpace

```c
// system/physmem.c

// 1. Create root MemoryRegion
MemoryRegion *system_memory = g_new(MemoryRegion, 1);
memory_region_init(system_memory, NULL, "system-memory", UINT64_MAX);

// 2. Create AddressSpace
AddressSpace *as = g_new(AddressSpace, 1);
address_space_init(as, system_memory, "system_memory");

// 3. Add subregions (RAM, MMIO, etc.)
MemoryRegion *ram = g_new(MemoryRegion, 1);
memory_region_init_ram(ram, NULL, "ram", 0x10000000, &error_fatal);
memory_region_add_subregion(system_memory, 0, ram);
```

