Section 2.3: address_space_rw vs cpu_physical_memory_rw

Two Ways to Access Guest Memory

address_space_rw():

· Takes an AddressSpace parameter
· Goes through MemoryRegion tree + FlatView
· Properly handles MMIO (calls callbacks)
· Safe for device emulation

cpu_physical_memory_rw():

· Uses address_space_memory implicitly
· Skips some checks (faster)
· Cannot be used for MMIO
· Used internally by QEMU

When to Use Which

```c
// 1. Device emulation: use address_space_rw()
void my_device_read(MyDevice *dev, hwaddr addr, void *buf, size_t len) {
    address_space_rw(&address_space_memory, addr, buf, len, true);
}

// 2. Internal QEMU code: use cpu_physical_memory_rw()
void qemu_loadvm_state(QEMUFile *f) {
    cpu_physical_memory_rw(addr, buf, len, true);
}

// 3. Fast path: use memory_region_get_ram_ptr()
void *ram_ptr = memory_region_get_ram_ptr(mr);
memcpy(ram_ptr + offset, buf, len);  // Direct access
```

Principal Insight: The fastest path is bypassing both and using memory_region_get_ram_ptr() directly. Used in high-performance devices (virtio-blk).

