Section 3.1: MemoryListeners

What is a MemoryListener?

A MemoryListener is notified on every AddressSpace change (region added/removed, size changed, etc.).

```c
struct MemoryListener {
    // Callbacks for region changes
    void (*region_add)(MemoryListener *l, MemoryRegionSection *section);
    void (*region_del)(MemoryListener *l, MemoryRegionSection *section);
    void (*region_nop)(MemoryListener *l, MemoryRegionSection *section);
    
    // Callbacks for address space changes
    void (*begin)(MemoryListener *l, AddressSpace *as);
    void (*commit)(MemoryListener *l, AddressSpace *as);
    
    // Dirty logging callbacks
    void (*log_start)(MemoryListener *l, MemoryRegionSection *section,
                      int old_flags, int new_flags);
    void (*log_stop)(MemoryListener *l, MemoryRegionSection *section,
                     int old_flags, int new_flags);
};
```

Who Uses MemoryListeners?

1. KVM (accel/kvm/kvm-all.c):

· Maps guest memory into KVM slots
· Updates on every region change
· Uses kvm_set_user_memory_region()

2. TCG (softmmu/physmem.c):

· Manages TLB flushing
· Invalides cached TBs on memory changes

3. VFIO (hw/vfio/common.c):

· Maps DMA regions
· Handles MMIO passthrough

4. Memory Dump (dump/dump.c):

· Copies memory for crash dump

Example: KVM MemoryListener

```c
// accel/kvm/kvm-all.c

static void kvm_region_add(MemoryListener *l, MemoryRegionSection *sec) {
    KVMMemoryListener *kml = container_of(l, KVMMemoryListener, listener);
    MemoryRegion *mr = sec->mr;
    
    // 1. Skip if not RAM
    if (!memory_region_is_ram(mr)) return;
    
    // 2. Get host address
    void *hva = memory_region_get_ram_ptr(mr) + sec->offset_within_region;
    hwaddr gpa = sec->offset_within_address_space;
    hwaddr size = sec->size;
    
    // 3. Add to KVM
    kvm_set_user_memory_region(kml->vmfd, gpa, size, hva, true);
}
```

Principal Insight: KVM's MemoryListener is why QEMU can scale to 10,000 VMs—it only notifies KVM when the memory map changes, not on every access.

