Section 3.2: Dirty Memory Tracking

Why Dirty Tracking?

Dirty tracking = which guest memory pages have been written to since last check.

Uses:

1. Live Migration: Only send dirty pages to destination
2. VGA: Track screen updates
3. Code generation: Invalidate TBs when code is written

Dirty Logging Mask

```c
// include/exec/memory.h

#define DIRTY_MEMORY_VGA        0  // VGA screen updates
#define DIRTY_MEMORY_MIGRATION  1  // Migration
#define DIRTY_MEMORY_CODE       2  // TCG code generation
#define DIRTY_MEMORY_NUM        3

// Each MemoryRegion has a bitmap
struct MemoryRegion {
    // ...
    uint8_t dirty_log_mask;      // Which dirty loggers are active
    unsigned long *dirty_bitmap; // Dirty bits (one per page)
};
```

Enabling Dirty Tracking

```c
// For migration
void ram_save_setup(QEMUFile *f, void *opaque) {
    MemoryRegion *mr;
    // Mark all RAM regions for dirty tracking
    RAMBlock *block = qemu_ram_foreach_block(ram_block_set_dirty, NULL);
}

void ram_block_set_dirty(RAMBlock *block) {
    memory_region_set_dirty(mr, 0, block->max_length);
}

// Check dirty pages
bool ram_dirty_pages(RAMBlock *block) {
    // Scan dirty bitmap
    for (int i = 0; i < block->pages; i++) {
        if (test_bit(i, block->dirty_bitmap)) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
}
```

Dirty Tracking Performance

Method Overhead Use Case
KVM dirty logging Low (hardware) Live migration, VGA
Software dirty tracking High TCG (code generation)
Page fault trapping Very high Debugging

Principal Insight: Dirty tracking is a necessary evil for live migration. The best optimization is to minimize how long a VM is dirty (use iterative migration + post-copy).

