NUMA-Aware Memory Allocation

```c
// backends/hostmem.c

typedef struct HostMemoryBackend {
    Object parent;
    uint64_t size;
    char *mem_path;          // Huge pages, etc.
    int policy;              // MPOL_DEFAULT, MPOL_BIND, etc.
    int *host_nodes;         // NUMA nodes
} HostMemoryBackend;

void host_memory_backend_memory_alloc(HostMemoryBackend *backend) {
    // 1. Allocate memory
    void *ptr = mmap(NULL, backend->size, PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE,
                     MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS, -1, 0);
    
    // 2. Set memory policy (NUMA)
    if (backend->policy == MPOL_BIND) {
        mbind(ptr, backend->size, MPOL_BIND, backend->host_nodes,
              backend->num_nodes, 0);
    }
    
    // 3. Register with QEMU
    qemu_ram_alloc_from_ptr(ptr, backend->size, backend->name);
}
```

Performance Implications

NUMA Configuration Bandwidth Latency
Local memory 50 GB/s 100 ns
Remote memory (one hop) 30 GB/s 200 ns
Remote memory (two hops) 20 GB/s 300 ns

Principal Insight: At top companies, NUMA awareness is critical. Always place guest memory and vCPUs on the same NUMA node.

